Omne etc.: ‘the existing universe is bounded in none of its dimensions.' nul. reg. ,vi.: Munro well explains, ‘ take which- ever of the roads through the universe you please‚ at no point in any of them will you reach its bound.' Cf. Epicurus in Diog. Laert. 10, 24, 41-2: ‘ And moreover the universe is infinite3 for that which is limited has an outside, and the outside is perceived in relation to something else. So that, not having an outside, it has no boundary3 and, not having a boundary, it must be infinite and not limited.' The Stoics, following Aristotle, taught that the universe is limited‚ but that outside of it there is unlimited extent of void space.
